Q1. Create a user-defined package mathops with a class Operations having methods add (), 
subtract (). Import it into another class and use it. 
package mathops;

public class Operations {
    public int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public int subtract(int a, int b) {
        return a - b;
    }
}
import mathops.Operations;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Operations op = new Operations();
        System.out.println("Addition: " + op.add(10, 5));
        System.out.println("Subtraction: " + op.subtract(10, 5));
    }
}
Q2. Show the use of all access modifiers (private, public, protected, and default) by creating 
variables and methods in different classes. 
class TestAccess {
    public int pubVar = 10;        // accessible everywhere
    private int priVar = 20;       // accessible only inside this class
    protected int proVar = 30;     // accessible in same package + subclasses
    int defVar = 40;               // default (package-private) → same package only

    public void publicMethod() {
        System.out.println("Public Method");
    }

    private void privateMethod() {
        System.out.println("Private Method");
    }

    protected void protectedMethod() {
        System.out.println("Protected Method");
    }

    void defaultMethod() {
        System.out.println("Default Method");
    }

    public int getPrivateVar() {
        return priVar;  // way to access private variable
    }
}

public class AccessDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TestAccess obj = new TestAccess();

        // Access public
        System.out.println("Public Var: " + obj.pubVar);
        obj.publicMethod();

        // Access private (only via getter)
        System.out.println("Private Var: " + obj.getPrivateVar());

        // Access protected & default (allowed since same package)
        System.out.println("Protected Var: " + obj.proVar);
        System.out.println("Default Var: " + obj.defVar);
    }
}

Q3.Create two packages: package1 with class A and package2 with class B. Access class A
from B using import.

package package1;

public class A {
    public void showMessage() {
        System.out.println("Hello from class A in package1!");
    }
}
package package2;

import package1.A; // importing class A

public class B {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A obj = new A();
        obj.showMessage();
    }
}

